  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening Response Mechanisms and Accountability to Gender-Based Violence in the North-East and Middle Belt of Nigeria (Phase II)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The crisis in conflict-affected north-east Nigeria continues to be one of the gravest in the world today, marked by armed conflict, forced displacement, and severe violations of civilians&apos; human rights and dignity. They are the main drivers of vulnerabilities and protection concerns that the vulnerable populations face, including protracted displacement, human rights violations, gender-based violence (GBV), and sexual exploitation and abuse (SEA). The objective of this project is to strengthen coordination among civil law enforcement agencies and community structures to ensure timely, accountable prevention and technical capacity to facilitate response services. This project builds on the achievements mentioned above and focus on improving access to direct response services for the crisis-affected populations as well as on continuing to build the capacity of the Nigeria Police Force (NPF) and the Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC), and the National Agency for Prohibition of Trafficking in Person (NAPTIP) to prevent and respond to GBV and trafficking in persons (TiP). Recognizing that the primary responsibility for protecting its people against violations of human rights rests with the state.</narrative>
  </description>
